something in your house.

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:10.960
Start there, and
put that money away.

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:13.659
Everyone should have a compound
interest account in the bank.

00:34:13.659 --> 00:34:15.429
I always tell, if
you're 20-something

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:18.460
and you put $5 a day away
in a compound interest,

00:34:18.460 --> 00:34:20.530
you will be a millionaire by 50.

00:34:20.530 --> 00:34:23.239
So let's just start there.

00:34:23.239 --> 00:34:27.080
One hour a week side
hustle, put the money away,

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:28.980
lower your overhead.

00:34:28.980 --> 00:34:31.280
It's really fun to
watch money grow.

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:33.920
When you have two
years of money saved,

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:39.139
two years of salary, one of
those years is for a rainy day.

00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:42.080
The other one is
your investment fund.

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:43.610
I want you to think--

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:45.340
you don't all have
to be entrepreneurs

00:34:45.340 --> 00:34:47.929
that create businesses-- what
are you going to invest in?

00:34:47.929 --> 00:34:48.570
Real estate?

00:34:52.530 --> 00:34:54.989
How much has real
estate gone up here?

00:34:54.989 --> 00:34:55.530
Crazy.

00:34:55.530 --> 00:34:57.030
SPEAKER 1: It's insane, yeah.

00:34:57.030 --> 00:34:59.040
NELY GALAN: If not, look
at a little business

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:01.920
down your street, some old
person that's going to retire

00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:03.570
and their kids don't
want the business.

00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:05.640
Pick something that
already exists.

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:07.800
Don't invent something.

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:11.110
That is for the
0.111 percentile.

00:35:11.110 --> 00:35:12.329
Franchises.

00:35:12.329 --> 00:35:14.370
You know what the number
one franchise in America

00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:14.920
is right now?

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:15.420
Tutoring.

00:35:18.900 --> 00:35:21.990
If I had to do my life over
again, I'd buy 20 franchises--

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:24.930
I'm going to make my kid buy
them-- of different sorts,

00:35:24.930 --> 00:35:28.590
food, yoga, tutoring, whatever.

00:35:28.590 --> 00:35:30.960
I mean, they give you the
color-by-number how to do it.

00:35:30.960 --> 00:35:33.280
Why does everything
have to be so hard?

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:35.820
You save some money,
put it in, and the thing

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:38.510
makes money while you sleep.

00:35:38.510 --> 00:35:42.020
So there are many, many,
many ways to become Self

00:35:42.020 --> 00:35:45.140
made, and we all
must do it, even

00:35:45.140 --> 00:35:46.640
if you work in a corporation.

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:48.800
You have to be an
intrapreneur and you

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:55.280
have to be cultivating your
entrepreneurial Self-Made life.

00:35:55.280 --> 00:35:57.992
SPEAKER 1: Looking
back, and I think

00:35:57.992 --> 00:35:59.450
I know the answer
to this, but what

00:35:59.450 --> 00:36:02.782
is your most proudest
moment looking back?

00:36:02.782 --> 00:36:03.990
NELY GALAN: Well, two things.

00:36:03.990 --> 00:36:07.340
Obviously, my son that I gave
birth to, which I don't even

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:10.410
know how I did that because I
didn't know what I was doing.

00:36:10.410 --> 00:36:13.200
But my parents are
very happy about that.

00:36:13.200 --> 00:36:14.774
And I have four stepkids.

00:36:14.774 --> 00:36:16.190
If I had to do my
life over again,

00:36:16.190 --> 00:36:18.770
I think I'd have more
kids because I think

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:21.100
that's a great part of life.

00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:23.450
SPEAKER 1: When did
you realize that?

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:26.230
NELY GALAN: When my time clock
was ticking so hard that--

00:36:26.230 --> 00:36:28.167
no, but I realized it now.

00:36:28.167 --> 00:36:29.750
I've realized it in
the last few weeks

00:36:29.750 --> 00:36:31.346
because my son is leaving.

00:36:31.346 --> 00:36:32.970
This is his senior
year in high school.

00:36:32.970 --> 00:36:35.870
And I'm like, why didn't I
have a few more waiting behind?

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:36.920
This is too much.

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:39.440
I left home and left
my mother there crying.

00:36:39.440 --> 00:36:40.430
Por favor, don't leave.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:41.390
And I left.

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:44.240
And now, I feel like,
man, karma's a bitch.

00:36:44.240 --> 00:36:48.050
But my other part is the moment
is that I started in television

00:36:48.050 --> 00:36:51.530
and I started college,
and I dropped out

00:36:51.530 --> 00:36:54.080
because I got so many
jobs in television.

00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:57.380
And really, at that
time an emerging field,

00:36:57.380 --> 00:37:00.360
my life experience
was really valuable.

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:02.210
But I always wanted
to go back to school,

00:37:02.210 --> 00:37:07.070
and I really felt as I got
older like there was real gaps--

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:10.010
not just in my education
because my business education

00:37:10.010 --> 00:37:11.330
I had gotten it in other ways--

00:37:11.330 --> 00:37:14.300
but my emotional
intelligence and my ability

00:37:14.300 --> 00:37:16.980
to read people and my
ability to do other things.

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:19.160
And so my second
proudest moment is

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:21.080
that I took a four-year
sabbatical, which

00:37:21.080 --> 00:37:23.870
for a type-A workaholic
is very hard to do.

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:27.650
So I only did it when I
felt like I had enough money

00:37:27.650 --> 00:37:28.610
to do it.

00:37:28.610 --> 00:37:30.260
And I went back to
school and I got

00:37:30.260 --> 00:37:32.510
a master's and doctorate in
clinical psychology, which

00:37:32.510 --> 00:37:33.660
I'm very proud of.

00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:36.110
So I can be all your shrinks.

00:37:36.110 --> 00:37:36.610
[APPLAUSE]

00:37:36.610 --> 00:37:38.193
And I don't think I
would have written

00:37:38.193 --> 00:37:40.160
this book had I not
done that because I

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:41.660
had to go back to school.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:45.290
My first professor said,
you write like a rapper.

00:37:45.290 --> 00:37:46.790
Because, you know,
I was in TV where

00:37:46.790 --> 00:37:49.030
there were pithy little
marketing things that I wrote.

00:37:49.030 --> 00:37:50.330
And he's like, here's
Strunk and White.

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:51.580
Learn to write all over again.

00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:53.510
And I go, I love this.

00:37:53.510 --> 00:37:56.390
And I ended up writing
97 papers and a thesis

00:37:56.390 --> 00:37:57.710
and a dissertation.

00:37:57.710 --> 00:37:59.930
And I don't think I would
have had the discipline

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:02.560
to go back and write
this book, which I

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:04.505
had done after going to school.

00:38:04.505 --> 00:38:06.380
SPEAKER 1: And tell us
what's on the horizon.

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:07.550
What's next?

00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:10.070
NELY GALAN: Well, I
have been on, as I said,

00:38:10.070 --> 00:38:11.550
a 130-city book tour.

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:13.230
I first need a rest.

00:38:13.230 --> 00:38:17.644
And I think my priority
for the rest of the year

00:38:17.644 --> 00:38:19.060
and into next year
early next year

00:38:19.060 --> 00:38:23.240
is, first of all, to analyze
what I've learned on the road.

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:26.499
I've met so many men and women.

00:38:26.499 --> 00:38:28.040
I feel like I've
been Hillary Clinton

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:32.690
for a year, city by city by city
meeting all kinds of people.

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.850
And I really want to
analyze that and figure out

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:36.680
what to do with
that information,

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:38.150
like a good entrepreneur.

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:39.740
But also, I want
to focus on my son.

00:38:39.740 --> 00:38:41.820
It's his last year
of high school,

00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:44.600
and I really want
to be there for him

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:46.130
and really help him out.

00:38:46.130 --> 00:38:49.670
And then, I'm very
open to all new things

00:38:49.670 --> 00:38:52.520
because I think the number
one thing that I would say

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:56.660
is important for all of us is
to evolve and grow everyday.

00:38:56.660 --> 00:39:00.260
There's so much that I know now
and so much that I've mastered

00:39:00.260 --> 00:39:03.020
and yet so much
that I don't know.

00:39:03.020 --> 00:39:05.870
And I think that we all have to
wake up every day understanding

00:39:05.870 --> 00:39:07.700
that we know nothing at all.

00:39:07.700 --> 00:39:09.950
And I think when
you think like that,

00:39:09.950 --> 00:39:12.200
magical things happen
to you, and you're

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:16.040
open to new ideas,
new possibilities.

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:18.770
And I'm right now
sitting on two years--

00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:21.950
and a book, where I did so
much research-- of knowledge

00:39:21.950 --> 00:39:24.140
that I have to
now spend the time

00:39:24.140 --> 00:39:27.110
to take all that research
and development that I've

00:39:27.110 --> 00:39:29.930
done and figure out
what do I do with that.

00:39:29.930 --> 00:39:32.990
SPEAKER 1: And any
advice for the Latinos

00:39:32.990 --> 00:39:35.370
here at Google and just
in the tech industry?

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:37.610
I know you're going to be
meeting hundreds of more

00:39:37.610 --> 00:39:38.120
Latinos.

00:39:38.120 --> 00:39:40.120
What do you think that
we should be thinking of,

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:41.886
and what can we
be doing more of?

00:39:41.886 --> 00:39:43.010
NELY GALAN: Well, I think--

00:39:43.010 --> 00:39:44.310
I mean, I've said this before--

00:39:44.310 --> 00:39:47.510
but you all have to
be louder and braver.

00:39:47.510 --> 00:39:51.920
It kills me to have everything
that's happened this year

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:54.800
and to have my
African-American friends say,

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:56.570
why are you Latinos so quiet?

00:39:56.570 --> 00:39:58.790
Why do you take it?

00:39:58.790 --> 00:40:01.220
And I understand why we
take it because that's

00:40:01.220 --> 00:40:04.130
how we were raised and
it's our parents baggage.

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:04.880
They're afraid.

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:10.609
But it's all of your jobs to
not carry that baggage with you.

00:40:10.609 --> 00:40:12.650
You have to know there's
nothing to be afraid of.

00:40:12.650 --> 00:40:14.490
No one is going to
do anything to you.

00:40:14.490 --> 00:40:15.385
It's all BS.

00:40:15.385 --> 00:40:16.510
Nothing is going to happen.

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:17.880
On the contrary.

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:22.040
And I think that the best advice
I can give you is sometimes I

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:24.410
understand that,
although I believe

00:40:24.410 --> 00:40:26.870
the answer for all of
us is uniting with all

00:40:26.870 --> 00:40:29.600
the other multiculturals
and learning from each other

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:33.106
because we all have different
traits and different skills,

00:40:33.106 --> 00:40:34.480
I understand that
sometimes let's

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:38.030
say our voice can't be the voice
of an African-American sister

00:40:38.030 --> 00:40:40.830
who is very empowered
and very strong.

00:40:40.830 --> 00:40:41.780
Maybe that's not us.

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:45.410
But one of our
super super powers

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:47.630
is we're very vulnerable people.

00:40:47.630 --> 00:40:51.530
And so sometimes, when someone
says something in front of you

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:53.471
and it's really like not cool--

00:40:53.471 --> 00:40:54.970
sometimes they don't
even mean, it's

00:40:54.970 --> 00:40:58.190
just that it's their learned
wiring and behavior--

00:40:58.190 --> 00:41:00.410
you have to say something
like, excuse me,

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:01.700
what did you just say?

00:41:01.700 --> 00:41:03.140
You just stabbed
me in the heart.

00:41:03.140 --> 00:41:05.920
That was so painful to hear.

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:09.370
That is so hurtful.

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:12.910
And that's just as strong
as saying, excuse me.

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:17.310
There is many ways to
skin the cat and be loud.

00:41:17.310 --> 00:41:19.110
Maybe it's not
always being loud.

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:22.330
Maybe it's being
honest and vulnerable.

00:41:22.330 --> 00:41:23.940
But we have to speak up.

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:27.960
I don't allow people to say
things about my culture--

00:41:27.960 --> 00:41:28.710
not in public.

00:41:28.710 --> 00:41:30.210
And by the way,
you don't think I

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:32.580
was afraid to go on Fox
News knowing that they

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:33.610
were going to ream me?

00:41:33.610 --> 00:41:36.390
I broke out in hives,
but I did it anyway.

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:39.390
And I didn't die.

00:41:39.390 --> 00:41:43.140
I said a few things about
immigrants, and on social media

00:41:43.140 --> 00:41:45.820
people were trolling
me like crazy.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:46.320
So what?

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:48.331
The next day it's over.

00:41:48.331 --> 00:41:49.330
You're not going to die.

00:41:49.330 --> 00:41:50.413
Nothing's going to happen.

00:41:50.413 --> 00:41:52.705
But you're going
to gain character.

00:41:52.705 --> 00:41:54.080
And there's
something that no one

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:59.570
can take away from you when you
speak on behalf of your family.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:01.880
SPEAKER 1: That's beautiful.

00:42:01.880 --> 00:42:04.520
I want to make sure that
you get any last remarks,

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:06.890
but I also want to see if
anyone here in the audience

00:42:06.890 --> 00:42:08.450
has questions for Nely.

00:42:08.450 --> 00:42:12.600
This has been my magic moment
at Google, having you here.

00:42:12.600 --> 00:42:14.630
It's been a while we've
been planning this,

00:42:14.630 --> 00:42:15.720
but I'm really excited.

00:42:15.720 --> 00:42:17.345
NELY GALAN: I'm so
proud of all of you.

00:42:17.345 --> 00:42:19.670
And Iliana, I'm so
proud of you, too.

00:42:19.670 --> 00:42:21.890
Love you guys.

00:42:21.890 --> 00:42:22.390
Yeah.

00:42:22.390 --> 00:42:23.135
So I want to hear questions.

00:42:23.135 --> 00:42:25.093
Don't you guys want to
know about Donald Trump?

00:42:27.480 --> 00:42:27.980
OK.

00:42:27.980 --> 00:42:31.160
So I'll just tell you a quick
"Celebrity Apprentice" story

00:42:31.160 --> 00:42:33.620
because I think you'll enjoy it.

00:42:33.620 --> 00:42:37.160
So when I ran
Telemundo, we sold it

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:41.110
and NBC gave me a very
big deal to produce shows.

00:42:41.110 --> 00:42:44.260
So I produced about 700
shows in English and Spanish.

00:42:44.260 --> 00:42:48.110
That's why I say I'm
Tyler Perry Latina.

00:42:48.110 --> 00:42:49.850
And I get a call
one day from NBC,

00:42:49.850 --> 00:42:52.308
and they said, we want you to
be on "Celebrity Apprentice."

00:42:52.308 --> 00:42:54.500
and I was like, well, I
produce reality shows.

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:56.000
I'm not in them.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:57.842
And they said, no.

00:42:57.842 --> 00:42:59.300
The president of
NBC said, I really

00:42:59.300 --> 00:43:03.020
think you would be great
because Donald Trump is tough.

00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:05.840
And we think if we put a
Latina actress or something,

00:43:05.840 --> 00:43:08.490
he might really insult them.

00:43:08.490 --> 00:43:11.690
You've worked for
six billionaires,

00:43:11.690 --> 00:43:13.160
and you've had them as clients.

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:14.910
And they're a lot worse
than Donald Trump.

00:43:14.910 --> 00:43:15.320
SPEAKER 1: You can take it.

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:16.730
NELY GALAN: You can take it.

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:19.190
And the truth is, I've
had to take it, you guys.

00:43:19.190 --> 00:43:20.540
I've worked in Hollywood.

00:43:20.540 --> 00:43:22.550
I have been yelled
at, screamed at.

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:24.170
I've had people be
very disrespectful,

00:43:24.170 --> 00:43:27.500
and I had to not take it
personally and put people

00:43:27.500 --> 00:43:28.290
in their place.

00:43:28.290 --> 00:43:31.430
I had to go into
my other persona.

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:32.380
So I said, all right.

00:43:32.380 --> 00:43:35.000
And they go, we're not asking
you, we're kind of telling you.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:36.320
And I was like, but
I'm not a celebrity.

00:43:36.320 --> 00:43:37.820
And they're like,
why don't you just

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:41.051
say thank you for millions
of dollars of publicity

00:43:41.051 --> 00:43:42.050
for your personal brand?

00:43:42.050 --> 00:43:43.970
And I was like, OK, thank you.

00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:45.910
And I went on
"Celebrity Apprentice."

00:43:45.910 --> 00:43:48.947
And in the first episode,
Donald Trump yelled at me.

00:43:48.947 --> 00:43:50.780
And in the first episode,
I did what I would

00:43:50.780 --> 00:43:51.905
have done with any of them.

00:43:51.905 --> 00:43:53.060
You saw me on the show.

00:43:53.060 --> 00:43:54.740
I would very
respectfully-- because I

00:43:54.740 --> 00:43:57.800
didn't do it, as I say in
Spanish, [SPEAKING SPANISH]..

00:43:57.800 --> 00:43:59.869
I would do it very
like, I'm sorry

00:43:59.869 --> 00:44:01.160
but no, I don't agree with you.

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:01.743
No, we're not.

00:44:01.743 --> 00:44:05.470
And we got into these
very feisty conversations.

00:44:05.470 --> 00:44:08.540
And after the first episode
when we were off camera,

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:12.230
he said to me, oh, it's so great
that you yelled back at me.

00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:13.220
How great.

00:44:13.220 --> 00:44:13.804
Keep doing it.

00:44:13.804 --> 00:44:15.303
We're going to get
a lot of ratings.

00:44:15.303 --> 00:44:17.400
Latinos will love you
because they don't like me,

00:44:17.400 --> 00:44:19.370
and it will be great that
you're yelling at me.

00:44:19.370 --> 00:44:22.490
And that tells you
a lot about him.

00:44:22.490 --> 00:44:24.830
He loves to argue for sport.

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:28.430
And he was very into the
ratings and very much

00:44:28.430 --> 00:44:30.770
the value of his property.

00:44:30.770 --> 00:44:34.640
But I actually had a great
time on "Celebrity Apprentice"

00:44:34.640 --> 00:44:38.300
because I was partnered up
with Gene Simmons from KISS.

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.550
And when he's not being
the guy from KISS,

00:44:40.550 --> 00:44:41.810
he's like a Jewish dad.

00:44:41.810 --> 00:44:43.280
He was very lovely.

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:44.840
And one day, he
says to me, Galan,

00:44:44.840 --> 00:44:47.450
you're such a smart
girl, but I feel

00:44:47.450 --> 00:44:50.150
like you're always climbing
a mountain the hardest

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:51.470
possible way.

00:44:51.470 --> 00:44:54.320
You're struggling like an
immigrant that just arrived.

00:44:54.320 --> 00:44:57.170
And I thought it was like he
was stabbing me in the heart

00:44:57.170 --> 00:44:59.210
because I thought that's true.

00:44:59.210 --> 00:45:00.890
Sometimes as Latinos
we don't even

00:45:00.890 --> 00:45:03.590
know how to enjoy the
journey if it's not hard,

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:06.350
if we're not struggling, if
it's not climbing a mountain

00:45:06.350 --> 00:45:08.210
the hardest possible way.

00:45:08.210 --> 00:45:10.340
And so I've given a
lot of thought to that,

00:45:10.340 --> 00:45:12.860
and I think what I need to
work on the rest of my life--

00:45:12.860 --> 00:45:16.490
because God knows I'm
not a baked cake--

00:45:16.490 --> 00:45:21.290
is achieving things with
ease versus struggling

00:45:21.290 --> 00:45:24.777
so much, having to suffer so
much to make things happen.

00:45:24.777 --> 00:45:27.276
AUDIENCE: Nely, quick question
on the commercial real estate

00:45:27.276 --> 00:45:29.410
front.

00:45:29.410 --> 00:45:32.590
What's the biggest lesson
learned or the hardest thing

00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:35.420
that you had to figure out
in commercial real estate?

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:40.580
NELY GALAN: Well, I think I
did find mentors in real estate

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:42.420
as well.

00:45:42.420 --> 00:45:43.870
I have a mentor in real estate.

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:46.954
Her name is Elaine,
and she's 75 years old.

00:45:46.954 --> 00:45:49.370
And one of those people that
I met that I just thought she

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:50.100
was brilliant.

00:45:50.100 --> 00:45:52.070
She was developing real estate.

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:54.950
And I started taking
her to dinner.

00:45:54.950 --> 00:45:56.810
And to this day,
she is my mentor.

00:45:56.810 --> 00:45:59.270
I don't buy a
building without her.

00:45:59.270 --> 00:46:00.370
I mean, at all.

00:46:00.370 --> 00:46:01.970
If she doesn't OK
the building, it

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:04.910
doesn't happen because, as
she has taught me very well,

00:46:04.910 --> 00:46:06.800
in real estate it's all math.

00:46:06.800 --> 00:46:08.180
And I have to tell
you something.

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:13.020
In my TV life, I've made five
times the money in real estate

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:14.420
than in my TV life.

00:46:14.420 --> 00:46:18.240
And I think it's because my TV
life is creative and emotional.

00:46:18.240 --> 00:46:20.330
Sometimes I've made
bad judgment calls

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:22.130
because I fall in
love with a show.

00:46:22.130 --> 00:46:24.080
I don't fall in
love with buildings.

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:26.820
If the math doesn't work,
you don't buy the building.

00:46:26.820 --> 00:46:28.400
Period.

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:32.000
So there's something
about mission and money,

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.670
having something in your life
that you love, and there's

00:46:34.670 --> 00:46:36.080
nothing wrong with that.

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:39.980
But until you're rich,
as my boss told me,

00:46:39.980 --> 00:46:42.800
the money part has
to take precedence

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:47.300
because you have so many years
of life force, of energy,

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:49.010
where if you're doing
five things at once

00:46:49.010 --> 00:46:51.046
I don't feel sorry
for you because you

00:46:51.046 --> 00:46:51.920
have a lot of energy.

00:46:51.920 --> 00:46:55.400
Later in your life, you're
not going to want to do that.

00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:57.770
So to me, yes, you
have to find mentors.

00:46:57.770 --> 00:47:01.010
You have to go to
events like this

00:47:01.010 --> 00:47:04.610
because if that's something
that interests you that is

00:47:04.610 --> 00:47:06.200
a path that works--

00:47:06.200 --> 00:47:08.930
linearly, slowly.

00:47:08.930 --> 00:47:12.980
All the tax incentives and all
the tax laws are in your favor.

00:47:12.980 --> 00:47:14.810
Hence, Donald Trump.

00:47:14.810 --> 00:47:18.320
When he says, I don't pay very
many taxes, he's not lying.

00:47:18.320 --> 00:47:19.680
That part is true.

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:24.200
All of us can pay lesser taxes
if we follow the tax laws

00:47:24.200 --> 00:47:29.291
and invest in things that
give us all kinds of benefits.

00:47:29.291 --> 00:47:30.915
AUDIENCE: Who are
your new role models,

00:47:30.915 --> 00:47:33.097
someone in the last five years?

00:47:33.097 --> 00:47:34.430
NELY GALAN: Well, I'll tell you.

00:47:34.430 --> 00:47:38.270
My role model that I
think about most often.

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:40.640
I have a few, but I
love Gloria Steinem

00:47:40.640 --> 00:47:43.610
because I love
Gloria Steinem at 85.

00:47:43.610 --> 00:47:45.680
She is beautiful.

00:47:45.680 --> 00:47:50.960
She is really deep and
profound and peaceful.

00:47:50.960 --> 00:47:52.490
And yet, she's still
doing her work.

00:47:52.490 --> 00:47:54.650
She still shows up and
speaks and all that.

00:47:54.650 --> 00:48:00.890
I also had a professor in school
who was 80-- at the time, 82,

00:48:00.890 --> 00:48:02.330
she's now 85--

00:48:02.330 --> 00:48:06.410
who had gone back to school
at 50 after raising five kids,

00:48:06.410 --> 00:48:10.620
had become the world's foremost
expert on Sigmund Freud,

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:12.950
has written six books
on Sigmund Freud.

00:48:12.950 --> 00:48:15.950
And now, she travels all
over the world lecturing

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:18.320
in her expertise,
which is Sigmund Freud.

00:48:18.320 --> 00:48:22.690
And at 82, she looked
like she was 50.

00:48:22.690 --> 00:48:25.100
And she really
inspired me in school

00:48:25.100 --> 00:48:27.410
to find, what is my true path?

00:48:27.410 --> 00:48:29.420
There's a lot of TV
producers, but what

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:32.060
I thought that I offer
the world uniquely

00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:34.310
is from a multicultural voice.

00:48:34.310 --> 00:48:38.420
I really walk the walk of
an entrepreneurial person,

00:48:38.420 --> 00:48:40.730
of a Self-Made woman.

00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:43.970
I've sacrificed what you need
to sacrifice to get to my age

00:48:43.970 --> 00:48:46.980
and be Self Made and be set.

00:48:46.980 --> 00:48:48.770
And I felt like it is my duty.

00:48:48.770 --> 00:48:52.790
And when I saw Sheryl, it
concretely was clear to me.

00:48:52.790 --> 00:48:55.310
It's my duty to pass that on--

00:48:55.310 --> 00:48:58.040
obviously, first to my
Latinas because I love you

00:48:58.040 --> 00:49:00.170
guys and I want you
all to succeed--

00:49:00.170 --> 00:49:03.800
then to other multicultural
women and men,

00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:07.670
and then to all young people
because I don't want everyone

00:49:07.670 --> 00:49:09.860
to think that you have
to be that one-of-a-kind,

00:49:09.860 --> 00:49:14.270
unicorn person that makes it
big when all of us can do it,

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:15.312
as I said, like a turtle.

00:49:15.312 --> 00:49:17.311
SPEAKER 1: I know we're
going to be doing a book

00:49:17.311 --> 00:49:19.810
signing after this, but I
want to thank you again,

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:23.570
Nely Galan, for being here,
joining us for Talks at Google

00:49:23.570 --> 00:49:26.090
in collaboration with Hola,
Google's Hispanic Googler

00:49:26.090 --> 00:49:28.910
network, and talking about
"Self Made," "New York Times"

00:49:28.910 --> 00:49:32.025
bestselling book, "Becoming
Empowered, Self-Reliant,

00:49:32.025 --> 00:49:33.275
and Rich in Every Single Way."

00:49:33.275 --> 00:49:34.670
NELY GALAN: Rich in every way.

00:49:34.670 --> 00:49:35.390
That's the key.

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:36.740
And why are we doing this?

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:41.570
To pass the torch to the next
generation of a mindset that

00:49:41.570 --> 00:49:44.090
is self-reliant, that
thinks like owners,

00:49:44.090 --> 00:49:46.490
that multicultural
people particularly

00:49:46.490 --> 00:49:49.576
think like owners
in everything we do.

00:49:49.576 --> 00:49:50.450
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:49:50.450 --> 00:49:51.366
NELY GALAN: Thank you.

